JQUERY EXERCISES – SOLUTIONS

1. jQuery Library Inclusion

Exercise 1: Adding jQuery to a Page

Solution:

1. Include jQuery using CDN:

<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.7.1.min.js"></script>

2. Include jQuery using a local file:

<script src="js/jquery-3.7.1.min.js"></script>

Bonus:

HTML:

<p id="msg">Hello World!</p>

jQuery:
$(document).ready(function(){
console.log($("#msg").text());
});

Output:
The text "Hello World!" is displayed on the webpage and logged in the browser console.

---

2. The $() Function

Exercise 2: Selecting Elements

HTML:

<h1 id="title">Original Heading</h1>

<p>Paragraph One</p>

<p id="hidePara">Paragraph Two</p>

<button id="btnHide">Hide Paragraph</button>

jQuery:
$(document).ready(function(){

```
$("#title").text("Welcome to jQuery");

$("#btnHide").click(function(){
    $("#hidePara").hide();
});
```

});

Output:
The heading changes to "Welcome to jQuery". Clicking the button hides the second paragraph.

---

3. jQuery Methods

Exercise 3: Use of Common Methods

HTML:

<div class="box"></div>
<div class="box"></div>
<div class="box"></div>

<button id="hideBtn">Hide</button> <button id="showBtn">Show</button> <button id="fadeOutBtn">Fade Out</button> <button id="fadeInBtn">Fade In</button> <button id="toggleBtn">Toggle</button>

jQuery:

$("#hideBtn").click(function(){
$(".box").hide();
});

$("#showBtn").click(function(){
$(".box").show();
});

$("#fadeOutBtn").click(function(){
$(".box").fadeOut();
});

$("#fadeInBtn").click(function(){
$(".box").fadeIn();
});

$("#toggleBtn").click(function(){
$(".box").toggle();
});

Bonus:

$(".box")
.slideUp()
.delay(1000)
.slideDown();

Output:
The boxes respond to different button clicks using jQuery effects.

---

4. DOM Manipulation

Exercise 4: Creating and Modifying Elements

HTML:

<input type="text" id="item">
<button id="addBtn">Add</button>
<button id="removeBtn">Remove All</button>

<ul id="list"></ul>

jQuery:

$("#addBtn").click(function(){

```
let value = $("#item").val();

if(value !== ""){

    $("#list").append(
        "<li>" + value + "</li>"
    );

    $("#item").val("");
}
```

});

$("#removeBtn").click(function(){
$("#list").empty();
});

Output:
The entered text is added to the list. Clicking "Remove All" clears the list.

---

5. Working with Events

Exercise 5: Handling User Interactions

HTML:

<button id="colorBtn">
Change Color
</button>

<div id="colorBox"></div>

jQuery:

$("#colorBtn").click(function(){

```
$("#colorBox").css(
    "background-color",
    "red"
);
```

});

$("#colorBtn").dblclick(function(){

```
$("#colorBox").css(
    "background-color",
    "white"
);
```

});

Output:
Single click changes the box color to red. Double click changes it back to white.

---

6. Event Helpers

Exercise 6: Mouse and Keyboard Events

HTML:

<div id="eventBox">
Hover or Click Me
</div>

<input
type="text"
id="inputBox"
placeholder="Type Here">

jQuery:

$("#eventBox").click(function(){

```
$(this).text(
    "Single Click Detected"
);
```

});

$("#eventBox").dblclick(function(){

```
$(this).css(
    "background",
    "yellow"
);
```

});

$("#eventBox").mouseenter(function(){

```
$(this).css(
    "background",
    "lightgreen"
);
```

});

$("#eventBox").mouseleave(function(){

```
$(this).css(
    "background",
    "white"
);
```

});

$("#inputBox").keypress(function(event){

```
alert(
    "Key Pressed: " +
    event.key
);
```

});

Output:

• click() – Changes text.
• dblclick() – Changes background color.
• mouseenter() – Changes background to light green.
• mouseleave() – Restores original color.
• keypress() – Displays the pressed key in an alert box.

Result:
All jQuery concepts such as library inclusion, selectors, methods, DOM manipulation, event handling, and event helpers were successfully implemented and tested.
